## Integrating container security solution into CI/CD Pipeline

Github link: [https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo](https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo)   
Firstly using [Trivy](https://github.com/aquasecurity/trivy) / [Trivy-operator](https://github.com/aquasecurity/trivy-operator) for a container image/multiple images.

Latest version of trivy (0.58.0) provides features like:

*   config      Scan config files for misconfigurations  
*   filesystem  Scan local filesystem  
*   image       Scan a container image  
*   kubernetes  \[EXPERIMENTAL\] Scan kubernetes cluster  
*   repository  Scan a repository  
*   rootfs      Scan rootfs  
*   sbom        Scan SBOM for vulnerabilities and licenses  
*   vm          \[EXPERIMENTAL\] Scan a virtual machine image

Thus would be a better alternative to Clair  
Trivy looks for open api keys in codebase, validates config files, also scans images for CVEs, or commonly exploited/ known vulnerabilities thus improving security of containers 

The configuration of implementing this solution is: [github](https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/assign/blob/main/TrivyVulnScan-to-SecHub.yaml)  
Using Github instead of AWS CodeCommit input project github repo is:  
[https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo](https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo)

Firstly when there is a commit to the above repository  then the pipeline begins, the image is built and trivy is initialized and scanning begins later the result of the vulnerabilitys is outputted onto a json. Output from trivy: [results.json](https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo/blob/main/results.json)

This result is later converted into [AWS Security Finding Format](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-findings-format.html) (ASFF), and then exports it to Security Hub through a python script: [sechub\_parser.py](https://github.com/phantomsoldierking/trivy-cicd-github-repo/blob/main/sechub_parser.py)

Finally the vulnerabilities are visible in security hub console of aws.

Also the images is deployed to ECS only if it has critical vulnerabilities (as of now)or some number of configured ones, thus preventing vulnerable images being deployed or reaching end user.

## Flow Diagram

A flow diagram illustrating the CI/CD pipeline integration for container security can be conceptualized as follows:

1. Code Commit: Developers commit code to the repository.(its discontinued using github)  
2. Build Stage: CI/CD pipeline triggers a build process using Docker.  
3. Vulnerability Scanning:  
   * Trivy/Clair scans the Docker image for vulnerabilities.  
   * Security reports are generated.  
4. Security Checks:  
   * Pre-deployment checks block vulnerable images.  
5. Deployment: Secure images are deployed to the Kubernetes cluster.  
6. Runtime Monitoring:  
   * Use of Falco/Aqua Security for monitoring anomalous activities.  
7. Logging: Centralized logging captures events from containers.  
8. Report Generation: Consolidated security reports are generated for review.

## Understanding of Project

The project entails several key components:

* Containerization with Docker: Applications will be packaged into lightweight containers using Docker, which facilitates easy deployment and scalability.  
* Vulnerability Scanning: Tools like Trivy and Clair will be integrated into the CI/CD pipeline to automatically scan images for known vulnerabilities. Trivy is known for its speed and accuracy in identifying vulnerabilities in OS packages and dependencies, while Clair provides deep analysis of container images.  
* Runtime Security: Implementing runtime security measures using tools such as Falco or Aqua Security will help detect anomalous behavior during the execution of containers. This is crucial for identifying potential threats in real-time.  
* Best Practices in Container Design:  
  * Minimize image layers to reduce the attack surface.  
  * Use non-root users to limit privileges within containers.  
  * Avoid hard-coded secrets by utilizing secret management solutions.  
*   
* Kubernetes Deployment and Monitoring: The containers will be deployed in a Kubernetes environment, where their behavior will be monitored through runtime analysis and centralized logging systems. This ensures that any irregularities can be quickly identified and addressed.
